: Detroit and the Fate of Postindustrial America -- tAppendix A. Index of Dissimilarity, Blacks and Whites in Major American Cities, 1940-1990 -- tAppendix B. African American Occupational Structure in Detroit, 1940-1970 -- tAbbreviations in the Notes -- tNotes -- tIndex  aOnce America's "arsenal of democracy," Detroit is now the symbol of the American urban crisis. In this reappraisal of America's racial and economic inequalities, Thomas Sugrue asks why Detroit and other industrial cities have become the sites of persistent racialized poverty. He challenges the conventional wisdom that urban decline is the product of the social programs and racial fissures of the 1960s. Weaving together the history of workplaces, unions, civil rights groups, political organizations, and real estate agencies, Sugrue finds the roots of today's urban poverty in a hidden history of racial violence, discrimination, and deindustrialization that reshaped the American urban landscape after World War II.This Princeton Classics edition includes a new preface by Sugrue, discussing the lasting impact of the postwar transformation on urban America and the chronic issues leading to Detroit's bankruptcy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aAfrican AmericanszMichiganzDetroitxEconomic conditionsy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszMichiganzDetroitxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aPovertyzMichiganzDetroitxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacismzMichiganzDetroitxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aSugrue, Thomas J.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311044418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400851218423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.